  "prompt": "How do the American and French Revolutions differ?",
  "response": "Here are key differences between the American and French Revolutions:\n\n1. Underlying Philosophies\n- American Revolution: Focused on political representation and individual rights\n- French Revolution: Driven by social class struggle and radical egalitarianism\n\n2. Social Context\n- American Revolution: Relatively stable colonial society challenging British rule\n- French Revolution: Profound social inequality with stark class divisions\n\n3. Violence Level\n- American Revolution: Relatively moderate, traditional military conflict\n- French Revolution: Extremely violent, including the Reign of Terror with mass executions\n\n4. Outcomes\n- American Revolution: Established a stable constitutional republic\n- French Revolution: Went through multiple political systems, including monarchy restoration and eventually Napoleon's rule\n\n5. Religious Dimensions\n- American Revolution: Emphasized religious freedom\n- French Revolution: Strongly anti-clerical, challenging the Catholic Church's power\n\n6. Economic Goals\n- American Revolution: Primarily about political representation and trade freedoms\n- French Revolution: Aimed to fundamentally restructure social and economic systems\n\n7. Leadership\n- American Revolution: Led by educated, property-owning elites\n- French Revolution: More populist, involving broader social classes\n\nWhile both were inspired by Enlightenment ideas of liberty and rights, they manifested quite differently in practice.",
